I agree with the recommendation of ***Andrew Morton***, however, I would like to clarify some details. To identify kilowatt-hours, I recommend that you use an international identifier from UNECE. E.g.:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &quot;priceSpecification&quot;:{
    &quot;@type&quot;:&quot;UnitPriceSpecification&quot;,
    &quot;price&quot;:&quot;0.27&quot;,
    &quot;priceCurrency&quot;:&quot;EUR&quot;,
    &quot;referenceQuantity&quot;: {
    &quot;@type&quot;:&quot;QuantitativeValue&quot;,
    &quot;value&quot;:&quot;1&quot;,
    &quot;unitCode&quot;:&quot;KWH&quot;,
    &quot;sameAs&quot;:&quot;http://www.unece.org/fileadmin/DAM/cefact/recommendations/bkup_htm/add3hk.htm&quot;
    }
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

In the content of a web page, it may be useful to use the **[HTML element abbr][1]** for an abbreviation of kilowatt-hours

Use the following recommendation for the **[price][2]** property: 

&gt; Use &#39;.&#39; (Unicode &#39;FULL STOP&#39; (U+002E)) rather than &#39;,&#39; to indicate a
&gt; decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

